John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to stand out for academic excellence. This continued with further outstanding exam results in 2018 and is only underpinned by individual and joint successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other joint ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest possible level of care for their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after in schools as elective subjects.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot only rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current results of this year's exam show that languages with the highest levels of existence are at the top of the ranking of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students learning foreign languages achieved grade A in the higher exams.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of Mandarin students achieved grade A in the higher exams, while 72 percent of German-learned students obtained grade A in 69 percent of French-learned students and 63 percent of Spanish-learned students also achieved grade A.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that will undoubtedly need children and young people in the future.
Languages are now regarded as elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014, 17 percent of the reasons given by employers for the problems in filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more vacancies require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalised world.
Irrespective of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong ability.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people a head start over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language spoken of a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
That is why it is important for the children of today that we now invest in language teaching.
Children who speak several languages, especially those of developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught at all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages that are considered to be the most important for the United Kingdom in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese, will teach.
Wherever your child's interests lie, in independent schools a number of languages will always be available with suitably specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, whatever the future looks like.
At this stage in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country, and this must therefore be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
