Harvard students learn to sleep enough in one class
A new course at Harvard University will make sure that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the spreading macho culture to keep up with caffeine and learn all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unneeded when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the USA.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
According to her, no one had ever told her how important sleep was. That surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which takes place for the first time this year, explained to the students how the basics of good sleeping habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the University's health services, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, the students see the image of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They receive information on the effects of caffeine and light as well as on the effects of lack of sleep on the athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the university grounds with interactive symbols.
"We know that it will not change the behaviour of the students immediately.
But we believe that you have the right to know – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a "night shift" is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made the lack of sleep a growing problem.
To ensure good sleep enough, the "secret weapon" of all students should be against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said. Furthermore, weight gain could be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course. He took one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study programme before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler's recommendation, students should set an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light", which can be caused by electronic screens and LED lighting, and which can get the circadian rhythm off the beat. This leads to problems when falling asleep.
