HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14°% in the number of people living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people in the country are affected.
About 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
In contrast to the past, the vast majority of new cases were transmitted through sexual intercourse.
So far, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way was almost zero, Chinese health officials reported at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 year-on-year.
HIV transmission through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but discrimination against members of the LGBT community is said to be widespread.
Based on the conservative values of the country, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sexual intercourse with men eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are due to insufficient protection during sexual intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has, among other things, promised universal access to HIV drugs to address the problem.
