National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
In an estate in the Scottish Highlands, new research is being carried out to show how bats use the landscape in the search for food.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will trace dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown long ear and water bats in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recorders are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
In a sound analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and which species does what.
A map and a report of the habitat will then be created to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for the bats and how these are used by each species.
These data will help to determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and to show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom as a whole have decreased significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to the loss of living space.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the topic of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who carry out regular examinations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threeve estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Governor David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
"Here in Threeve we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there are many things we don't yet know about bats, so here and in other goods, we do these works that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He stressed the importance of excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it was possible that the involuntary destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and wipe out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many of our species do not know what their populations are like."
