"The fact that a quick political decision in either Washington or Beijing could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized," says Abigail Grace, a research associate focused on Asia in the Center for New American Security think tank.
Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, said the Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the more than seven years of war.
Speaking to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country was improving.
"Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer," he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
All the conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed aid to rebuild the devastated country.
He stressed, however, that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won back the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the US.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems with much of the tournament, sank his tee on the 16th course (par 3) in the water and lost against Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in the team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It's been a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I'm so infinitely happy to win the trophy back.
It's about the team and I'm happy to have made a contribution," said emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch on to his compatriot John Rahm, who won 2-1 in the individual encounters against the American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday.
I am so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I have been watching on TV since my childhood," says 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all his four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA had problems finding the fairways all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who have done high-quality performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the boys, they fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put pressure on Europe.
We didn't make anything of it.
Hat off for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players performed well.
We're going to regroup, I'm going to talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup Committee, and we're going to look ahead.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You have to pull your hat.
We were defeated."
Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more patchy flowering conditions are recorded in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algal bloom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from north Pinella to south of the Lee district.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the last week, mean concentrations were reported in or off the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinella, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems became known during the last week.
